Spring:
  The Spring Framework is a lightweight, open-source Java framework used to build enterprise-level applications. 
  It mainly provides infrastructure support so you can focus on business logic.
Benefits of Spring Framework:
  1. Loose Coupling - Classes are independent → easy to maintain
  2. Easy Testing - Supports unit and integration testing
  3. Lightweight - uses POJO
  4. Flexible & Modular - uses only required modules
  5. Reduces Boilerplate Code - replace XML's over annotations
  6. Scalable & Enterprise Ready - Used in large-scale systems
  7. Integration friendly - intergrates with DB, API's and messaging system.
Limitations of Spring Framework:
  1. learning curve - Beginners struggle with Annotations, Configurations and AOP concepts
  2. Complexity in Large Projects - Too many annotations can confuse and Debugging becomes harder
  3. Performance Overhead - Reflection & proxy usage adds slight overhead
  4. Configuration Overload (without Spring Boot) - xml based config was heavy 
  5. Hidden Magic (Auto Configuration) - hard to understand whats happening
  
Core Features of Spring Framework:
Spring Core: The Spring Core is the foundation module of the Spring Framework.
    It provides:
                IoC (Inversion of Control) Container
                Dependency Injection (DI)
                Bean lifecycle management
                Everything in Spring (MVC, Boot, Security) depends on this

IoC Container in Spring:
  The Inversion of Control (IoC) container is the heart of the Spring Framework.
  It is responsible for:
    Creating objects (beans)
    Injecting dependencies
    Managing lifecycle
    Configuring relationships
  
Traditional: OrderService os = new OrderService(new PaymentService());
Spring (IoC):
    You don’t create objects
    Spring container creates & injects them
    Control is inverted → given to Spring

Types of IOC:
  1. Bean Factory (Basic Container) :  Old, minimal container
      Lazy initialization (creates bean only when needed)
      Lightweight
      No advanced features
      BeanFactory factory = new XmlBeanFactory(new ClassPathResource("beans.xml"));     
      What happens:
                  XML loaded
                  Bean definitions stored
                  Bean NOT created ❌
                  When getBean() called → bean created ✅ OrderService os = factory.getBean("orderService"); This is lazy loading
  2. ApplicationContext: Most used in real-world
      Eager initialization (default)
      Supports:
      AOP
      Events
      Internationalization (i18n)
      Annotation-based config
Types of ApplicationContext:
      1. ClassPathXmlApplicationContext - Loads Spring configuration from XML files present in classpath
            Uses classpath (src/main/resources) 
            Eager initialization by default
            Supports: Constructor injection and Setter injection    
            Limitations: XML heavy, Hard to maintain in large apps and Not used in modern Spring Boot projects
            usage: Legacy applications and Older enterprise systems
          working:
            Reads XML file
            Parses <bean> definitions
            Creates objects
            Injects dependencies
          example:
          <beans>
              <bean id="paymentService" class="com.app.PaymentService"/>
              <bean id="orderService" class="com.app.OrderService">
                  <property name="paymentService" ref="paymentService"/>
              </bean>
          </beans>

          ApplicationContext context = new ClassPathXmlApplicationContext("beans.xml");
          OrderService os = context.getBean("orderService", OrderService.class); 
          👉 What happens:
                        XML loaded
                        Bean definitions read
                        ALL singleton beans created immediately ✅ ✔ This is eager loading
                        Dependencies injected
                        Lifecycle methods executed
      BeanFactory vs ApplicationContext:
      BeanFactory:
        BeanFactory factory = new XmlBeanFactory(...);
        // No object created yet ❌
        factory.getBean("paymentService"); // Object created here ✅
      ApplicationContext:
        ApplicationContext context = new ClassPathXmlApplicationContext("beans.xml"); 
        // Object created immediately ✅

      2. AnnotationConfigApplicationContext - Modern way: uses Java-based configuration + annotations
            No XML required ✅
            Uses: @Component, @Service and @Repository
            Type-safe configuration
            Easy to maintain
         usage: Core Spring (non-Boot apps) and Microservices (before Boot)
         Working:
          Reads @Configuration class
          Scans packages (@ComponentScan)
          Creates beans using annotations
        Internal Flow:
          Reads @Configuration
          Performs component scanning
          Registers beans in container
          Applies DI (@Autowired)
          Initializes beans
          @Configuration
          @ComponentScan("com.app")
          public class AppConfig {}

          @Component
          public class PaymentService {}

          ApplicationContext context =new AnnotationConfigApplicationContext(AppConfig.class);     
          PaymentService ps = context.getBean(PaymentService.class);

      3. SpringBootApplication (internally uses this) - This is from Spring Boot. It is a combination of 3 annotations:
          @SpringBootApplication - @Configuration, @EnableAutoConfiguration and @ComponentScan
          No XML 
          Auto configuration 
          Embedded server 
          Production-ready
          What Container Does It Use?
          Internally, Spring Boot uses:
              ✔ AnnotationConfigApplicationContext (for non-web apps)
              ✔ AnnotationConfigServletWebServerApplicationContext (for web apps)
          @SpringBootApplication
          public class App {
              public static void main(String[] args) {
                  SpringApplication.run(App.class, args);
              }
          }
          When you run: SpringApplication.run(App.class, args);
            Creates ApplicationContext
            Detects type: for Web → Servlet context and for Non-web → Standard context
            Starts component scanning
            Applies auto-configuration
            Creates all beans
            Starts embedded server (Tomcat)
        👉 You add dependency: Spring Data JPA
        👉 Boot automatically configures: DataSource, EntityManager and Hibernate

Dependency Injection (DI):
      Objects depend on each other via injection.
      Instead of creating dependencies manually (PaymentService ps = new PaymentService();) , Spring injects them.
      Types of Dependency Injection:
        1. Constructor Injection ✅ (Best Practice)
        @Component
        public class OrderService {
            private final PaymentService ps;
            public OrderService(PaymentService ps) {
                this.ps = ps;
            }
        }
        ✔ Advantages: Immutable, Thread-safe and Mandatory dependencies enforced
      2. Setter Injection
          public void setPaymentService(PaymentService ps) {
              this.ps = ps;
          }
        ✔ Used when: Dependency is optional
      3. Field Injection ❌ (Avoid)
        @Autowired
        private PaymentService ps;
        ❌ Problems: Hard to test and Breaks encapsulation

Autowiring in Spring:
  Autowiring = Automatic dependency injection by Spring
  Types of Autowiring:
    1. By type - Matches by class type
    2. By name - Matches variable name with bean name
    3. Constructor - public OrderService(PaymentService ps) {} (Spring automatically injects)
  Problem: Multiple Beans: If 2 implementations exist → error
                      @Autowired
                      PaymentService ps;
  Solution: use @Qualifier or @Primary 

Bean Wiring: How Spring connects beans together
`1. Manual Wiring (XML) 🧓 Old Way
        <bean id="paymentService" class="com.app.PaymentService"/>
        <bean id="orderService" class="com.app.OrderService">
            <property name="paymentService" ref="paymentService"/>
        </bean>
  2. Annotation-Based Wiring ✅ (Modern)
        @Component
        public class OrderService {
            @Autowired
            private PaymentService ps;
        }
  3. Java Config Wiring
        @Configuration
        public class AppConfig {        
            @Bean
            public PaymentService paymentService() {
                return new PaymentService();
            }   
            @Bean
            public OrderService orderService() {
                return new OrderService(paymentService());
            }
        }

Eager vs Lazy Initialization:
  Eager Initialization (Default in ApplicationContext) : Beans are created at startup
  Flow:
    Application starts
    All singleton beans created immediately
   ✔ Advantages: Errors detected early and Application ready faster at runtime
  ❌ Disadvantages: Slow startup if many beans
 Lazy Initialization: Beans created only when needed
    To Enable Lazy:
              using Annotation:
              @Lazy
              @Component
              class PaymentService {}
              Or globally: spring.main.lazy-initialization=true
  ✔ Advantages: Faster startup and Saves memory
 ❌ Disadvantages: Errors occur at runtime and First call is slower

Spring Bean Lifecycle:
  A bean lifecycle is the complete internal process by which the Spring Framework: Creates → Configures → Initializes → Uses → Destroys a bean
  Big Picture (Internal Flow):
    Load BeanDefinition → Instantiate Bean → Populate Dependencies →
    Aware Interfaces → BeanPostProcessor (Before) →
    Init Methods → BeanPostProcessor (After) →
    Ready → Destroy
  Step-by-Step Internal Lifecycle:
  1. Bean Definition Loading : Spring reads configuration (XML / Annotation / Java Config)
      Internally: Creates BeanDefinition object 
      ✔ Contains: Class name, Scope, Dependencies and Init/Destroy methods 
      👉 Core classes: BeanDefinition and BeanDefinitionReader
  2. Bean Instantiation: Object is created using: Constructor and Factory method
    Internally: createBeanInstance()
    👉 Core class: AbstractAutowireCapableBeanFactory
    ✔ Uses: Reflection and Constructor resolution
  3. Dependency Injection (Populate Properties) - Inject dependencies into bean
    Internally: populateBean()
    ✔ Handles: @Autowired, Setter injection and Field injection  
    👉 Uses: AutowiredAnnotationBeanPostProcessor
  4. Aware Interfaces (Container Awareness)- 
    If bean implements:
              BeanNameAware
              BeanFactoryAware
              ApplicationContextAware   
    👉 Spring calls:
              setBeanName()
              setBeanFactory()
              setApplicationContext()
    Purpose: Gives bean access to container internals
  5. BeanPostProcessor (Before Initialization) - Hook to modify bean before init
      postProcessBeforeInitialization()
      ✔ Use cases: Logging,Validation and Custom proxy creation
    👉 Interface: BeanPostProcessor
  6. Initialization Phase - Three ways (priority order matters 🔥):
       1. @PostConstruct (Recommended)
                  @PostConstruct
                  public void init() {}
       2. InitializingBean- afterPropertiesSet()
       3. Custom init method - @Bean(initMethod = "init")
     Internally handled by: invokeInitMethods()
  7. BeanPostProcessor (After Initialization)
        postProcessAfterInitialization()
    VERY IMPORTANT:  This is where AOP proxy is created
    ✔ Example: Transactional proxy and Security proxy
  8. Bean Ready for Use : Now bean is: Fully initialized, Stored in singleton cache
    Internally:DefaultSingletonBeanRegistry
  9. Destruction Phase - Happens when container shuts down
      Methods:
      1. @PreDestroy
          @PreDestroy
          public void cleanup() {}
      2. DisposableBean - destroy()
      3. Custom destroy method -  @Bean(destroyMethod = "destroy")
   Internally: destroyBean()

Complete Internal Lifecycle Chain
        BeanDefinition →
        createBean() →
        populateBean() →
        Aware Interfaces →
        BeanPostProcessor (before) →
        @PostConstruct →
        afterPropertiesSet →
        custom init →
        BeanPostProcessor (after) →
        READY →
        destroyBean()

Important Internal Classes:
 1. DefaultListableBeanFactory-  Core container implementation
  ✔ Responsibilities: Stores bean definitions and Manages bean creation
 2. AbstractAutowireCapableBeanFactory -  Handles: Instantiation  and Dependency injection
 3. BeanPostProcessor-  Custom lifecycle hook
  ✔ Example: AOP - @Autowired processing
 4. BeanFactoryPostProcessor -  Runs BEFORE bean creation
 ✔ Modifies: BeanDefinition metadata
 5. AutowiredAnnotationBeanPostProcessor -  Handles: @Autowired injection

How Spring creates an object (bean) inside the IoC container:
  There are multiple ways to instantiate a bean, and interviewers often expect you to know all of them with use cases.  
  1. Using Default Constructor (Most Basic) - Spring calls the no-argument constructor using reflection.
        @Component
        public class UserService {
            public UserService() {
                System.out.println("Bean created");
            }
        }
    ✔ Spring automatically instantiates it during startup.
    Internal Method: createBeanInstance()
    ✔ Uses reflection internally
 2. Using Parameterized Constructor (Constructor Injection) - Spring chooses a constructor and injects dependencies.
        @Component
        public class OrderService {
        
            private PaymentService ps;
        
            public OrderService(PaymentService ps) {
                this.ps = ps;
            }
        }
    ✔ Spring: Finds constructor, Resolves dependencies and Instantiates bean
    If multiple constructors: Use @Autowired or primary constructor
  3. Using Static Factory Method - Spring calls a static method to create bean.
        public class PaymentService {
            public static PaymentService getInstance() {
                return new PaymentService();
            }
        }
        XML: <bean id="paymentService" class="com.app.PaymentService" factory-method="getInstance"/>
    ✔ Useful for: Legacy code and Singleton control
 4. Using Instance Factory Method - Spring uses another bean to create the object.
        public class FactoryClass {
            public PaymentService createService() {
                return new PaymentService();
            }
        }
        XML:<bean id="factory" class="com.app.FactoryClass"/>
        <bean id="paymentService"
              factory-bean="factory"
              factory-method="createService"/>
    ✔ Useful for: Complex object creation logic
 5. Using @Bean Annotation (Java Config) - Bean is created inside a configuration class.
        @Configuration
        public class AppConfig {
            @Bean
            public PaymentService paymentService() {
                return new PaymentService();
            }
        }
    ✔ Most common in modern Spring
  6. Using @Component Scanning (Auto Instantiation) - Spring scans package and automatically creates bean.
      @Component
      public class PaymentService {}
   ✔ Combined with: @ComponentScan("com.app")
   ✔ This is most used in Spring Boot
  7. Using Supplier (Advanced - Functional Style) -Register bean programmatically
      context.registerBean(PaymentService.class,
          () -> new PaymentService());
   ✔ Used in: Dynamic bean creation
 8. Using Bean Definition Programmatically (Advanced) - Manually register bean definition
      GenericBeanDefinition bd = new GenericBeanDefinition();
      bd.setBeanClass(PaymentService.class);
      beanFactory.registerBeanDefinition("ps", bd);
  ✔ Used in:Framework development
